GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 813
Short Title: Enhanced Reg. of Registered Res. Facilities. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Pittman, Clark, and Crawford (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Appropriations, if favorable, Finance, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and
Operations of the House
April 8, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT REPLACING THE TERM "MULTIUNIT ASSISTED HOUSING WITH SERVICES"
3 WITH "REGISTERED RESIDENTIAL FACILITY" AND REDEFINING THE TERM
4 "ASSISTED LIVING RESIDENCE" TO EXCLUDE THESE FACILITIES TO MAKE IT
5 CLEARER TO THE PUBLIC THAT REGISTERED RESIDENTIAL FACILITIES ARE
6 NOT EQUIVALENT TO LICENSED ADULT CARE HOMES; UPDATING THE
7 REGISTRATION REQUIREMENTS FOR REGISTERED RESIDENTIAL FACILITIES;
8 EXPANDING THE LIST OF PERSONS NOT TO BE CARED FOR IN REGISTERED
9 RESIDENTIAL FACILITIES; AUTHORIZING THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND
10 HUMAN SERVICES TO SEEK AN INJUNCTION OR OTHER PROCESS AGAINST A
11 REGISTERED RESIDENTIAL FACILITY OPERATING WITHOUT APPROVED
12 REGISTRATION; AND DIRECTING THE MEDICAL CARE COMMISSION TO ADOPT
13 RULES ESTABLISHING STANDARDS FOR REGISTERING, INSPECTING, AND
14 TAKING ADVERSE ACTION AGAINST REGISTERED RESIDENTIAL FACILITIES.
15 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
16 SECTION 1. Effective January 1, 2026, Part 1 of Article 1 of Chapter 131D of the
17 General Statutes reads as rewritten:
18 "Part 1. Licensing.
19 …
20 "§ 131D-2.1. Definitions.
21 As used in this Article:
22 …
23 (5) Assisted living residence. – Any group housing and services program for two
24 or more unrelated adults, by whatever name it is called, that makes available,
25 at a minimum, one meal a day and housekeeping services and provides
26 personal care services directly or through a formal written agreement with one
27 or more licensed home care or hospice agencies. The Department may allow
28 nursing service exceptions on a case-by-case basis. Settings in which services
29 are delivered may include self-contained apartment units or single or shared
30 room units with private or area baths. Assisted living residences are to be
31 distinguished from nursing homes subject to provisions of G.S. 131E-102.
32 There are three two types of assisted living residences: adult care homes,
33 homes and adult care homes that serve only elderly persons, and multiunit
*H813-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 assisted housing with services. persons. As used in this section, "elderly
2 person" means:
3 a. Any person who has attained the age of 55 years or older and requires
4 assistance with activities of daily living, housing, and services, or
5 b. Any adult who has a primary diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease or other
6 form of dementia who requires assistance with activities of daily
7 living, housing, and services provided by a licensed Alzheimer's and
8 dementia care unit.
9 …
10 (10) Multiunit assisted housing with services. – An assisted living residence in
11 which hands-on personal care services and nursing services which are
12 arranged by housing management are provided by a licensed home care or
13 hospice agency through an individualized written care plan. The housing
14 management has a financial interest or financial affiliation or formal written
15 agreement which makes personal care services accessible and available
16 through at least one licensed home care or hospice agency. The resident has a
17 choice of any provider, and the housing management may not combine
18 charges for housing and personal care services. All residents, or their
19 compensatory agents, must be capable, through informed consent, of entering
20 into a contract and must not be in need of 24-hour supervision. Assistance
21 with self-administration of medications may be provided by appropriately
22 trained staff when delegated by a licensed nurse according to the home care
23 agency's established plan of care. Multiunit assisted housing with services
24 programs are required to register annually with the Division of Health Service
25 Regulation. Multiunit assisted housing with services programs are required to
26 provide a disclosure statement to the Division of Health Service Regulation.
27 The disclosure statement is required to be a part of the annual rental contract
28 that includes a description of the following requirements:
29 a. Emergency response system;
30 b. Charges for services offered;
31 c. Limitations of tenancy;
32 d. Limitations of services;
33 e. Resident responsibilities;
34 f. Financial/legal relationship between housing management and home
35 care or hospice agencies;
36 g. A listing of all home care or hospice agencies and other community
37 services in the area;
38 h. An appeals process; and
39 i. Procedures for required initial and annual resident screening and
40 referrals for services.
41 Continuing care retirement communities, subject to regulation by the
42 Department of Insurance under Chapter 58 of the General Statutes, and
43 temporary family health care structures, as defined in G.S. 160D-915, are
44 exempt from the regulatory requirements for multiunit assisted housing with
45 services programs.
46 …
47 (12a) Registered residential facility. – A nonlicensed residence for two or more
48 unrelated adults, by whatever name it is called, in which the housing
49 management arranges for a licensed home care or hospice agency to provide
50 hands-on personal care services and nursing services to residents through an
51 individualized written care plan. Continuing care retirement communities,
