8 "§ 131D-2.2A. Requirements for registered residential facilities; compliance with
9 disclosure statement; Department's right to inspect.
10 (a) Registration. – Registered residential facilities shall apply annually for registration
11 with the Division of Health Service Regulation (Division) on forms and in the manner prescribed
12 by the Division. The Division shall approve registration for any registered residential facility that
13 meets all of the requirements of this section and pays the registration fee required by
14 G.S. 131D-2.5(b).
15 (b) Disclosure Statement. – In order to be approved for registration by the Division, a
16 registered residential facility shall provide a disclosure statement with its completed registration
17 application that includes a description of all of the following items, services, and requirements:
18 (1) The facility's emergency response system and an explanation of how the
19 resident should call for emergency assistance.
20 (2) Charges for rentals or services offered by the facility, which shall not be
21 changed without at least 30 days' written notice to residents.
22 (3) Any limitations of tenancy.
23 (4) Any limitations of services, including any services not provided by the
24 registered residential facility and procedures for initiating termination of a
25 rental contract due to changes in a resident's condition or due to other reasons.
26 (5) Resident responsibilities.
27 (6) Any financial or legal relationship between the housing management and any
28 licensed home care or hospice agencies referred by the housing management
29 to residents.
30 (7) A listing of all licensed home care and hospice agencies and other community
31 services located in the same area as the facility and their contact information.
32 (8) An appeals process for any dispute between the facility and a resident related
33 to rental charges, charges for services, or termination of a rental contract.
34 (9) Procedures for initial and annual resident screening as required by subsection
35 (d) of this section and procedures for the facility to make referrals of services
36 to residents.
37 (10) Contact information for the Division of Health Service Regulation Complaint
38 Intake Unit complaint hotline and the appropriate county department of social
39 services.
40 (11) Contact information for the owner or manager of the registered residential
41 facility as well as information on the number and type of staff available at the
42 facility and a schedule of on-site working hours at the facility.
43 The Division shall approve or disapprove the disclosure statement as a part of the registration
44 process. Upon approval of its disclosure statement and registration application, a registered
45 residential facility has a continuing duty to comply with the disclosure statement and is required
46 to notify the Division within 14 days after making any change to a disclosure statement approved
47 by the Division. The registered residential facility shall include the approved disclosure statement
48 as part of the resident's annual rental contract and shall ensure that the resident or the resident's
49 legal representative signs the approved disclosure statement on an annual basis.
50 (c) Agreement for Housing and Services. – The housing management of a registered
51 residential facility is required to have a financial interest, or financial affiliation, or formal written
Page 4 House Bill 813-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 agreement that makes personal care services accessible and available to residents through at least
2 one licensed home care or hospice agency. The housing management shall give each resident a
3 choice of any provider and keep charges for housing and personal care services separate. The
4 housing management shall ensure that all residents, or their compensatory agents, are capable,
5 through informed consent, of entering into a contract for housing and services.
6 (d) Resident Screening. – Each registered residential facility shall conduct an initial
7 screening of each resident prior to admission and then a follow-up screening at least once
8 annually. The purpose of the initial and annual screenings required by this subsection is to
9 identify a resident's need for assistance with activities of daily living, independent activities of
10 daily living, and any ancillary services needed to maintain the resident's safety, well-being, and
11 functional status. A registered residential facility shall make service referrals to each resident
12 based on that resident's screenings. A registered residential facility may assist a resident with
13 self-administration of medications if the assistance is provided by appropriately trained staff and
14 a licensed nurse has approved the delegation of medication assistance according to the home care
15 agency's established plan of care for the resident.
16 (e) Handling of Resident Funds Prohibited. – A registered residential facility and its
17 owners, agents, employees, and other persons affiliated with the registered residential facility are
18 prohibited from serving as a resident's legal representative or payee, or handling a resident's
19 funds.
20 (f) Employee Background Checks. – A registered residential facility is prohibited from
21 hiring or using as a volunteer any individual listed on the North Carolina Health Care Personnel
22 Registry established under G.S. 131E-256. A registered residential facility shall not hire any
23 employee prior to conducting a criminal history background check of the employee and shall not
24 refer any licensed home care or hospice agency to a resident prior to verifying that the licensed
25 home care or hospice agency conducts criminal history background checks of its employees.
26 (g) Adverse Action by the Division of Health Service Regulation. – The Division of
27 Health Service Regulation may deny, suspend, or revoke the registration of a registered
28 residential facility for any of the following reasons:
29 (1) Upon a determination by the Division that a facility is providing services that
30 require a license rather than registration.
31 (2) Upon a determination by the Division that a facility is not in compliance with
32 its approved disclosure statement.
33 (3) Upon a determination by the Division that a county department of social
34 services has substantiated a finding of abuse, neglect, or exploitation by a
35 facility. Any owner of a registered residential facility whose registration is
36 revoked by the Division under this subdivision is prohibited from registering
37 another registered residential facility or applying for a license to operate
38 another health care facility under this Chapter, Chapter 122C, Chapter 131E,
39 or Article 7 of Chapter 110 of the General Statutes for a period of 60 months
40 following the date of the revocation.
41 Any facility wishing to contest the Division's actions under this subsection is entitled to an
42 administrative hearing as provided in the Administrative Procedure Act, Chapter 150B of the
43 General Statutes.
44 (h) Adverse Action by the Secretary. – The Secretary may deny, suspend, amend, or
45 revoke the registration of a registered residential facility, or suspend the admission of any new
46 residents to a registered residential facility, in any case in which the Secretary finds that there
47 has been a substantial failure to comply with this Part, any applicable rules adopted under this
48 Part, or any other applicable State laws or rules. Any facility wishing to contest the Secretary's
49 actions under this subsection is entitled to an administrative hearing as provided in the
50 Administrative Procedure Act, Chapter 150B of the General Statutes.
House Bill 813-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (i) Duty to Report Suspected Abuse, Neglect, and Exploitation of Residents. – A
2 registered residential facility that knows or has cause to suspect that a resident is being abused,
3 neglected, or exploited shall report this information to local law enforcement, the North Carolina
4 Health Care Personnel Registry pursuant to G.S. 131E-256, and the appropriate county
5 department of social services in accordance with G.S. 108A-102.
6 (j) Complaint Inspections and Plans of Correction. – Each registered residential facility
7 registered under this Part is subject to inspection at all times by the Secretary to investigate
8 complaints filed with the Division against the facility alleging violations of this Part. A registered
9 residential facility shall permit the Division to inspect the premises and all facility and resident
10 records upon request. Within 15 working days after conducting an inspection authorized by this
11 subsection, the Division shall send a written report of its findings to the registered residential
12 facility. Within 10 working days after receipt of the Division's written report of findings, the
13 registered residential facility shall submit a plan of correction to the Division, based on the
14 written report of the findings, that describes steps the registered residential facility will take to
15 achieve and maintain compliance with the requirements of this Part. A registered residential
16 facility's failure to submit a plan of correction within the time period prescribed by this section
17 or failure to submit a plan of correction that is acceptable to the Division is grounds for the
18 Division to take adverse action on the registered residential facility's registration.
19 "§ 131D-2.3. Exemptions from licensure.
20 The following are excluded from this Article and are not required to be registered or obtain
21 licensure under this Article:
22 (1) Facilities licensed under Chapter 122C or Chapter 131E of the General
23 Statutes.
24 (2) Persons subject to rules of the Division of Employment and Independence for
25 People with Disabilities.
26 (3) Facilities that care for no more than four persons, all of whom are under the
27 supervision of the United States Veterans Administration.
28 (4) Facilities other than registered residential facilities that make no charges for
29 housing, amenities, or personal care service, either directly or indirectly.
30 (5) Institutions that are maintained or operated by a unit of government and that
31 were established, maintained, or operated by a unit of government and exempt
32 from licensure by the Department on September 30, 1995.
33 …
34 "§ 131D-2.5. License and registration fees.
35 …
36 (b) The Department shall charge each registered multiunit assisted housing with services
37 program residential facility a nonrefundable annual registration fee of three hundred fifty dollars
38 ($350.00). Any individual or corporation that establishes, conducts, manages, or operates a
39 multiunit housing with services program, registered residential facility subject to registration
40 under this section, that fails to register is guilty of a Class 3 misdemeanor and, upon conviction
41 shall be punishable only by a fine of not more than fifty dollars ($50.00) for the first offense and
42 not more than five hundred dollars ($500.00) for each subsequent offense. Each day of a
43 continuing violation after conviction shall be considered a separate offense.
44 "§ 131D-2.6. Legal action by Department.
45 (a) Notwithstanding the existence or pursuit of any other remedy, the Department may,
46 in the manner provided by law, maintain an action in the name of the State for injunction or other
47 process against any person to restrain or prevent the establishment, conduct, management, or
48 operation of (i) an adult care home without a license. license or (ii) a registered residential facility
49 without approved registration. Such action shall be instituted in the superior court of the county
50 in which any unlicensed activity has occurred or is occurring.
