1 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 143B-165 reads as rewritten:
2 "§ 143B-165. North Carolina Medical Care Commission – creation, powers and duties.
3 There is hereby created the North Carolina Medical Care Commission of the Department of
4 Health and Human Services with the power and duty to adopt rules to be followed in the
5 construction and maintenance of public and private hospitals, medical centers, and facilities
6 regulated under Chapters 131D and 131E of the General Statutes; to adopt, amend and rescind
7 rules under and not inconsistent with the laws of the State as necessary to carry out the provisions
8 and purposes of this Article; and to protect the health, safety, and welfare of the individuals
9 served by these facilities.
10 …
11 (14) The Commission shall adopt rules establishing standards for the following
12 with respect to facilities used as multiunit assisted housing with services,
13 registered residential facilities, as defined by Article 1 of Chapter 131D of the
14 General Statutes:
15 a. Registration and deregistration.
16 b. Disclosure statements.
17 c. Agreements for services.
18 d. Personnel requirements.
19 e. Resident admissions and discharges.
20 f. Inspections.
21 g. Approval, denial, revocation, or amendment of a facility's registration,
22 and suspension of admissions at a facility."
23 SECTION 2.(b) The Medical Care Commission may adopt emergency rules in
24 accordance with G.S. 150B-21.1A to implement this section with a reference to this subsection
25 as the basis for the adoption of those rules as emergency rules. Notwithstanding
26 G.S. 150B-21.1A(a), the Medical Care Commission shall not commence the adoption of
27 temporary rules pursuant to this subsection. Notwithstanding G.S. 150B-21.1A(d)(4), an
28 emergency rule adopted pursuant to this subsection expires on the earlier of January 1, 2027, or
29 the date the permanent rules adopted by the Medical Care Commission pursuant to
30 G.S. 143B-165(14), as amended by this act, become effective. The Department of Health and
31 Human Services shall notify the Revisor of Statutes when the permanent rules adopted pursuant
32 to G.S. 143B-165(14), as amended by this act, take effect.
33 SECTION 3. Effective January 1, 2026, G.S. 131E-256(b) reads as rewritten:
34 "(b) For the purpose of this section, the following are considered to be "health care
35 facilities":
36 (1) Adult Care Homes as defined in G.S. 131D-2.1.
37 (2) Hospitals as defined in G.S. 131E-76.
38 (3) Home Care Agencies as defined in G.S. 131E-136.
39 (4) Nursing Pools as defined by G.S. 131E-154.2.
40 (5) Hospices as defined by G.S. 131E-201.
41 (6) Nursing Facilities as defined by G.S. 131E-255.
42 (7) State-Operated Facilities as defined in G.S. 122C-3(14)f.
43 (8) Residential Facilities as defined in G.S. 122C-3(14)e.
44 (9) 24-Hour Facilities as defined in G.S. 122C-3(14)g.
45 (10) Licensable Facilities as defined in G.S. 122C-3(14)b.
46 (11) Multiunit Assisted Housing with Services Registered residential facilities as
47 defined in G.S. 131D-2.1.
48 (12) Community-Based Providers of Services for the Mentally Ill, the
49 Developmentally Disabled, and Substance Abusers that are not required to be
50 licensed under Article 2 of Chapter 122C of the General Statutes.
